Requirements
MATLAB R2021a or newer recommended
No external toolbox is strictly required for the main simulation
exportgraphics support is needed for figure export
How to Run
Open MATLAB in the repository folder.
Run the main script:
main_model
Output figures and tables will be saved automatically in the figures/ directory.
Outputs

The script generates, among others, the following outputs:

Spatially averaged dynamics panel
Six-panel biological summary
Validation figures
Clinical viral-load comparison
Cross-sectional spatial profiles
Virus--temperature coupling figure
Temporal convergence table
Shape-parameter sensitivity analysis
Three-dimensional spatial snapshots
GIF-style rotating surfaces of selected final-state variables
Biological Interpretation

The model is intended to provide a mechanistic and spatially resolved description of within-host SARS-CoV-2 infection. It is not currently calibrated to patient-level longitudinal data and should therefore be interpreted primarily as a biologically grounded qualitative framework rather than as a patient-specific predictive tool.

Limitations
Parameters were selected to produce biologically plausible qualitative dynamics
Temperature is modeled as a downstream marker rather than a feedback modulator
Sensitivity analysis is local rather than global
Explicit Euler time integration may require replacement for stiffer regimes
The main simulation script uses finite-difference Laplacians, while supplementary shape-parameter analysis explores RBF-related behavior
Future Work

Potential extensions include:

formal parameter estimation,
Bayesian calibration with clinical viral-load data,
global sensitivity analysis,
fully meshless RBF collocation implementation for the full PDE system,
bioheat transport coupling,
pharmacokinetic/pharmacodynamic treatment modules,
and three-dimensional patient-specific geometries.
Citation

If you use this repository in academic work, please cite the corresponding paper and reference this code repository.
